Additive Functional Cox Model

Erjia Cui

2020-10-09

We introduce the Additive Functional Cox Model (AFCM) and show its application to the National Health and Nutritional Examination Survey (NHANES) data. Based on the selection creteria discussed at Section 1 of the paper, 2816 participants from the 2003-2004 and 2005-2006 waves of NHANES study are included. In this vignette we show (1) how to fit our model on untransformed or transformed functional covariates using the gam() function in the mgcv package, (2) how to calculate cross-validated c-index for each model and compare their predictive performance.

For simulation, we introduce a novel framework generating survival data with functional predictors which resemble the observed data. We also show how to calculate integrated squared error (ISE) to evaluate the estimation performance.

Pre-processing

Suppose we observe independently censored survival outcome, and at baseline we observe \(p\) scalar covariates \(\mathbf{Z}_i\) and a functional covariate \(\mathbf{X}_i = \{X_i(s): s \in \mathcal{S}\}\). Denote \(X_i^\mathcal{P}(s) = \{X_i(u): u \leq s\}\). We posit Additive Functional Cox Model: \[\log \lambda_i(t|\mathbf{Z}_i, \mathbf{X}_i) = \log \lambda_0(t) + \mathbf{Z}_i^T \mathbf{\beta} + \int_\mathcal{S} F\{s, h_{is}[X_i^\mathcal{P}(s)]\}ds\;,\] where \(F(\cdot, \cdot)\) is an unspecified bivariate twice differentiable function, and \(h_{is}(\cdot)\) is a transformation function on the partial history of functional covariate \(X_i^\mathcal{P}(s)\). In this vignette, we simplify the discussion of transformation on functional covariate \(X_i(s)\).

To model the time to event outcome, we censor all mortality data at 10 years.

## censor mortality data in 10 years
data_analysis$event[which(data_analysis$time_mort > 10)] <- 0
data_analysis$time_mort[which(data_analysis$time_mort > 10)] <- 10

In practice, we only observe functional covariates on a discrete grid of functional domain. To approximate the integral of the functional term in the model using numerical summation, we next introduce and calculate relevant variables tmat and lmat.

## add intergral related variables
### function "cal_tind()" returns number of observations per subject (nt) and location of each time point in [0,1] (tind)
#### tlen: time interval, 1-minute by default as discussed in the paper
cal_tind <- function(tlen = 1){
    nt <- floor(1440/tlen) ## number of observations per subject
    tind <- seq(0, 1, len=nt) ## location of each time point in [0, 1]
    return(list(nt = nt, tind = tind))
}
### lmat: numeric integration of the functional term
data_analysis$lmat <- I(matrix(1/cal_tind(1)$nt, ncol=cal_tind(1)$nt, nrow=nrow(data_analysis)))
### tmat: time indices, [0, 1] in our case, but effectively arbitrary
data_analysis$tmat <- I(matrix(cal_tind(1)$tind, ncol=cal_tind(1)$nt, nrow=nrow(data_analysis), byrow=TRUE))
### the time interval is by hour in age-specific quantile transformation 
data_analysis$lmat_qa <- I(matrix(1/cal_tind(60)$nt, ncol=cal_tind(60)$nt, nrow=nrow(data_analysis)))
data_analysis$tmat_qa <- I(matrix(cal_tind(60)$tind, ncol=cal_tind(60)$nt, nrow=nrow(data_analysis), byrow=TRUE))

Transformation of functional covariates

We discussed various types of transformations \(h_{is}(X_i(s))\) in the paper. Here we focus on three of them, including identity, quantile-transformation, and age-specific quantile-transformation. The functional covariate \(X_i(s)\) is the smoothed log-transformed activity counts (smoothed LAC), as discussed in the paper. Note that the processed data frame data_analysis contains the unsmoothed LAC in the act_log_mat column.

We first derive the smoothed LAC using fpca.face() function in the refund package and save it as act_log_mat_sm in the data_analysis. In this case, \(h_{is}(X_i(s)) = X_i(s)\). We then perform the quantile transformation on smoothed AC. In this case, \(h_{is}(X_i(s)) = \text{P}\{X(s) \leq X_i(s)|s\}\), where \(\{X(s): s \in \mathcal{S}\}\) is the stochastic process on the functional domain and \(X_i(s)\) is the observed functional realization for the \(i{\text{th}}\) study participant. Note that the range of \(h_{is}(X_i(s))\) is changed to \([0,1]\). The quantile-transformed smoothed AC is denoted as act_log_mat_sm_q.

## derive untransformed and transformed functional covariates
## 1. smoothed LAC
data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm   <- I(fpca.face(unclass(data_analysis$act_log_mat))$Yhat)
## 2. quantile-transformed smoothed LAC
data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_q <- I(apply(data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm, 2, function(y) ecdf(y)(y)))

The last implemented transformation is age-specific quantile-transformation, where \(h_{is}(X_i(s)) = \text{P}(X(s) \leq X_i(s)|s, \mathbf{U}_i)\). Here \(\mathbf{U}_i\) refers to the covariate age in data_analysis. Since the mqgam() function from qgam package is time-consuming under such sample size, we provide the code without running it in this vignette for time purpose. However, it is implementable and takes several hours on a regular laptop.

#! The code is implementable, taking several hours on a regular laptop
#! Implemented in the manuscript, by default not implemented in this vignette for efficiency
## 3. age-specific quantile-transformed smoothed LAC
### bin activity profile by hour (mqgam function is very time consuming for large nt)
data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_hour <- I(data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm[,c(0:23)*60/5+1])
### construct data frame to perform age-specific quantile transformation
data_qreg <- data.frame("y" = as.vector(t(data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_hour)),
                        "t" = rep(cal_tind(60)$tind, nrow(data_analysis)),
                        "age" = rep(data_analysis$Age, each=cal_tind(60)$nt))
### create quantile vector (precision = 0.01 in our example)
quantile <- seq(0.01, 0.99, by = 0.01)

### fit the additive quantile regression model for each quantile -- time consuming
#! When building the vignette, we do not actually fit this model to save time.
#! If you would like to reproduce all the plots in Figure 4, it is necessary to run this step
#! Otherwise please skip all steps related to age-specific quantile transformation below
fit <- mqgam(list(y ~ te(t,age, bs=c("cc","cr"),k=c(5,5)), ~ s(t, bs="cc")) , data=data_qreg, qu = quantile)

### derive and add pre-smoothed and age-specific quantile-transformed AC
data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_qa <- I(matrix(0, nrow = nrow(data_analysis), ncol = cal_tind(60)$nt))
for(i in 1:nrow(data_analysis)){
    mat <- matrix(0, nrow = length(quantile), ncol = cal_tind(60)$nt)
    ## for each individual, extract the quantile matrix of its age
    for(j in 1:length(quantile)){
        mat[j,] <- fit$fit[[j]]$fitted.values[which(data_qreg$age == data_analysis$Age[i])][1:24]
    }
    ## find the approximate quantile at each time
    for(t in 1:ncol(mat)){
        data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_qa[i, t] <- quantile[max(which(mat[,t] < data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_hour[i, t]))]
    }
}
rm("data_qreg")

In addition, we derive the daily average smoothed LAC of each participant, denoted as act_log_mat_ave. It is a scalar covariate used to fit the baseline Cox proportional hazard model when comparing predictive performance.

## 4. average smoothed LAC as a scalar predictor
data_analysis$act_log_mat_ave <- rowSums(data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm) / ncol(data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm)

Apply Additive Functional Cox Model to NHANES

In this section, we describe how to apply our model to different functional predictors in NHANES and extract the estimates on area of interest.

Reproduce Figure 4

In the exploratory plots (Figure 3), we observe no data of high activity counts at night for all NHANES participants. To make this fact clearer, we further draw the density plots of physical activity under different transformations among both deceased and alive individuals. In each panel, we divide the area of interest into certain number of blocks and summarize the number of events and nonevents in each block; see the application section of the paper for details. This is implemented using the cal.evnt function below.

## calculate the number of events and nonevents on the grid under each transformation
### function "cal.evnt" returns the number of events and nonevents on the grid for given functional data
#### mat: the functional data
#### n.block.s: number of blocks on s direction, by default 24
#### n.block.x: number of blocks on x direction, by default 20
#### range.x: manually set upper bound of x, if NULL use the range of data
#### lower.x: manually set lower bound of x, by default 0
cal.evnt <- function(mat, n.block.s = 24, n.block.x = 20, range.x = NULL, lower.x = 0){
    ## derive the range of the grid
    range.s <- ncol(mat)
    if(is.null(range.x)){
        range.x <- ceiling(2*max(mat))/2  
    }
    ## set range of each sub-domain
    num.sub.s <- n.block.s
    num.sub.x <- n.block.x
    ## get number of value of functional covariates in each sub-domain
    num.event.sub <- matrix(0, nrow = num.sub.s, ncol = num.sub.x)
    num.nonevent.sub <- matrix(0, nrow = num.sub.s, ncol = num.sub.x)
    for(i in 1:num.sub.s){
        ls <- floor((i-1)*range.s/num.sub.s) + 1
        rs <- floor(i*range.s/num.sub.s)
        sub <- as.matrix(mat[,ls:rs])
        for(j in 1:num.sub.x){
            lx <- lower.x + (j-1)*(range.x-lower.x)/num.sub.x
            ux <- lower.x + j*(range.x-lower.x)/num.sub.x
            ind <- c()
            for(k in 1:nrow(sub)){
                if(length(which(sub[k,] >= lx & sub[k,] < ux)) > 0){
                    ind <- c(ind, k)
                }
            }
            num.event.sub[i, j] <- table(data_analysis[ind,]$event)["1"]
            num.nonevent.sub[i, j] <- table(data_analysis[ind,]$event)["0"]
        }
    }
    num.event.sub[which(is.na(num.event.sub))] <- 0
    num.nonevent.sub[which(is.na(num.nonevent.sub))] <- 0
    
    return(list(num.event.sub = num.event.sub, num.nonevent.sub = num.nonevent.sub, 
                range.s = range.s, range.x = range.x, lower.x = lower.x))
}

## unsmoothed LAC
cal.evnt.log <- cal.evnt(data_analysis$act_log_mat, range.x = 8)
## smoothed LAC
cal.evnt.log.sm <- cal.evnt(data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm, range.x = 8)
## quantile-transformed smoothed LAC
cal.evnt.log.sm.q <- cal.evnt(data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_q)

Indeed, quantile transformation substantially improves the estimability on the area of interest, as we see a much better coverage on the right two panels.

Fit Additive Functional Cox Model

We build a tensor product on the functional covariates when fitting our model using gam() function in the mgcv package. In the pre-processing we introduce some variables related to calculating the numerical integration of functional term. To be specific, t_int is the time indices on \([0,1]\) indicating all time points of observations, l_int is the interval length between each two adjacent time points, and func_cov is the functional covariates. We are aware of two approaches to ensure identifiability. The first approach first obtains unconstrained estimate then subtracts the corresponding sample mean. The second approach directly impose marginal identifiability constraints when specifying the tensor product, which is implemented by default in this vignette. Both approaches solve the identifiability issue and the estimates are indistinguishable. The comparison of these two approaches is in the supplementary materials of the paper.

Using the second approach, the tensor product is specified as ti(t_int, func_cov, by=l_int, bs=c("cc","cr"), k=c(Kx,Kt), mc = (FALSE, TRUE)), where bs indicates the type of splines used in each direction, k indicates the number of spline basis functions in each direction, and mc indicates whether to specify marginal constraints in each direction. The mc = TRUE argument on func_cov direction coincides with the identifiability constraints discussed in Section 2.3 of the paper.

The following variables are included as scalar covariates: socio-demographic factors (age, race, employment status, education attainment, poverty-income ratio), health factors (self-reported overall health,smoking status, alcohol consumption, body mass index, mobility difficulty) and disease indicators(diabetes, coronary heart disease, congestive heart failure, stroke, cancer, systolic blood pressure, total cholesterol).

## smoothed LAC, h_{is} is the identity function
data_analysis$func_cov <- data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm ## specify the functional covariates to use
data_analysis$t_int <- data_analysis$tmat ## t_int helps to integrate the case when models have different tmat and lmat
data_analysis$l_int <- data_analysis$lmat
fit_afc_log_sm <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Employed +
                       Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                       CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer +
                       ti(t_int, func_cov, by=l_int, bs=c("cc","cr"), k=c(10,10), mc=c(FALSE,TRUE)), weights=event,
                   data=data_analysis, family=cox.ph())

## quantile-transformed smoothed LAC, h_{is} is the quantile transformation
data_analysis$func_cov <- data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_q 
data_analysis$t_int <- data_analysis$tmat
data_analysis$l_int <- data_analysis$lmat
fit_afc_log_sm_q <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Employed +
                        Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                        CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer +
                        ti(t_int, func_cov, by=l_int, bs=c("cc","cr"), k=c(5,5), mc=c(FALSE,TRUE)), weights=event,
                    data=data_analysis, family=cox.ph())

We provide the code to fit AFCM using age-specific quantile-transformed smoothed LAC. Note that the t_int and l_int in this model are different from above models due to different number of observations when performing age-specific quantile-transformation.

#! The code is implementable only if you fit the additive quantile regression model above and derive act_log_sm_qa
#! Implemented in the manuscript, not implemented in this vignette
## age-specific quantile-transformed smoothed LAC
### observation bined by hour in this case
data_analysis$func_cov <- data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_qa
data_analysis$t_int <- data_analysis$tmat_qa ## tmat_qa is different from other tmat
data_analysis$l_int <- data_analysis$lmat_qa
fit_afc_log_sm_qa <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Age + Employed +
                         Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                         CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer +
                         ti(t_int, func_cov, by=l_int, bs=c("cc","cr"), k=c(5,5), mc=c(FALSE,TRUE)), weights=event,
                     data=data_analysis, family=cox.ph())

Reproduce Figure 5

We extract the estimates on a pre-specified grid constructed using cal_grid() function with specified range of value of functional covariates (range_x), range of functional domain (range_s), and the length of grid in each direction (grid_length).

## construct the grid (100*100 matrix by default) with specified ranges
### function "cal_grid()" returns grid (grid_coef) with pre-specified range of x and s
#### grid_length: length of grid in each direction, 100 by default
#### range_x: pre-specified upper bound of x, 1 by default
#### range_s: pre-specified upper bound of s, 1 by default
cal_grid <- function(grid_length = 100, range_x = 1, range_s = 1){
    tind_pred <- seq(0, range_s, length.out = grid_length)
    xind_pred <- seq(0, range_x, length.out = grid_length)
    grid_coef <- data.frame(t_int = rep(tind_pred, grid_length),
                            func_cov = rep(xind_pred, each = grid_length),
                            l_int=1)
    return(grid_coef)
}

Since several scalar covariates are included, all of them are required to use the predict() function to derive the predicted value on the grid of functional term, though their values do not affect the prediction results of functional term. Here we replicate the scalar covariates of the first subject to build the prediction matrix. In applications to different data, the sample here should be adjusted based on the covariates used in the model.

## add other variables used in model fitting, required in predict() function
### in practice, we replicate the first row in final grid since it won't incluence estimated functional surface
sample <- data_analysis[1, c("Alcohol", "Overall_health", "PIR", "Age", "Employed", "BMI_cat", 
                        "SmokeCigs", "Race", "Education", "CHD", "Diabetes", "CHF", "Stroke",
                        "MobilityProblem", "Cancer")]

We next derive the estimates. If we use the first approach to handle identifiability, a post-hoc correction is necessary. However now we directly impose the identifiability constraints in model fitting, so no correction is needed.

## smoothed LAC
grid_coef <- cal_grid(grid_length = 100, range_x = 8, range_s = 1) ## range_x based on maximum of act_log_mat
sample_rep <- do.call("rbind", replicate(nrow(grid_coef), sample, simplify = FALSE))
grid_coef <- cbind(grid_coef, sample_rep)
real_coef_afc_log_sm <- predict(fit_afc_log_sm, newdata = grid_coef, type = 'terms')
real_coef_afc_log_sm <- matrix(real_coef_afc_log_sm[,"ti(t_int,func_cov):l_int"], ncol = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), nrow = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), byrow = FALSE) # re-organize to matrix form

## quantile-transformed smoothed LAC
grid_coef <- cal_grid(grid_length = 100, range_x = 1, range_s = 1) ## quantile transformation ensures range of x is [0, 1]
sample_rep <- do.call("rbind", replicate(nrow(grid_coef), sample, simplify = FALSE))
grid_coef <- cbind(grid_coef, sample_rep)
real_coef_afc_log_sm_q <- predict(fit_afc_log_sm_q, newdata = grid_coef, type = 'terms')
real_coef_afc_log_sm_q <- matrix(real_coef_afc_log_sm_q[,"ti(t_int,func_cov):l_int"], ncol = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), nrow = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), byrow = FALSE) # re-organize to matrix form
#! The code is implementable only if you fit the additive quantile regression model above and derive act_log_sm_qa
#! Implemented in the manuscript, not in this vignette
## age-specific quantile-transformed smoothed LAC
grid_coef <- cal_grid(grid_length = 100, range_x = 1, range_s = 1) 
sample_rep <- do.call("rbind", replicate(nrow(grid_coef), sample, simplify = FALSE))
grid_coef <- cbind(grid_coef, sample_rep)
real_coef_afc_log_sm_qa <- predict(fit_afc_log_sm_qa, newdata = grid_coef, type = 'terms')
real_coef_afc_log_sm_qa <- matrix(real_coef_afc_log_sm_qa[,"ti(t_int,func_cov):l_int"], ncol = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), nrow = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), byrow = FALSE) # re-organize to matrix form

We use the vis_surf() function to visualize the estimates, which is essentially a wrapper of ggplot2.

### function "vis_surf()" returns the visualization of functional surface using ggplot2 package
#### coef: the matrix to visualize
#### simulation: indicate whether the plot is for application (FALSE) or simulation (TRUE)
#### transformation: indicate whether the functional covariates are transformed (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
#### range_x: the upper bound of functional value domain
#### range_s: the upper bound of functional domain
#### trans_name: name of the transformation
vis_surf <- function(coef, simulation = FALSE, transformation = TRUE, range_x = 1, range_s = 1, 
                     trans_name = "smoothed LAC"){
    coef_plot <- melt(coef) # re-organize to plot form
    grid_length <- nrow(coef) ## length of grid in each direction
    ## when the surface is from real data, x axis is time of a day, y axis is transformed AC
    if(simulation == FALSE){
        if(transformation == TRUE){
            name_y <- expression(h[is](log(1 + AC)))
        }else{
            name_y <- expression(log(1 + AC))
        }
        surf <- ggplot(coef_plot, aes(Var1,Var2, fill = value)) + 
            geom_raster() +
            scale_fill_gradientn(colours=c("blue3", "#FFFFFF", "#F67F7F", "#FF0000"), name = expression(hat(F)(.,.))) +
            ggtitle(trans_name) +
            scale_x_continuous(name = "Time of day",
                               breaks = c(1, floor(0.25 * grid_length), floor(0.5 * grid_length), floor(0.75 * grid_length), grid_length),
                               labels = c("00:00","06:00", "12:00", "18:00", "24:00")) +
            scale_y_continuous(name = name_y, 
                               breaks = floor(seq(0, floor(range_x), length.out = 5) / range_x * grid_length), 
                               labels = seq(0, floor(range_x), length.out = 5)) +
            theme_minimal() + 
            theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 15, hjust = 0.5))
    }else{ ## when the surface is from simulated data, x axis is the functional domain, y axis is the functional value domain,
        surf <- ggplot(coef_plot, aes(Var1,Var2, fill = value)) + 
            geom_raster() +
            scale_fill_gradientn(colours = c("blue3", "#FFFFFF", "red2"), name = expression(hat(F)(.,.))) +
            ggtitle(trans_name) +
            scale_x_continuous(name = "Functional domain",
                               breaks = floor(seq(0, floor(range_s), length.out = 6) / range_s * grid_length), 
                               labels = seq(0, floor(range_s), length.out = 6)) +
            scale_y_continuous(name = "Value of functional covariate",
                               breaks = floor(seq(0, floor(range_x), length.out = 6) / range_x * grid_length), 
                               labels = seq(0, floor(range_x), length.out = 6)) +
            theme_minimal() + 
            theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 15, hjust = 0.5))
    }
    return(surf)
}

### function "vis_stratified()" returns the visualization of functional surface from stratified analysis
#### period: "night" or "day"
#### grid_length: length of grid in each direction
vis_stratified <- function(period, grid_length = 100){
    if(period == "night"){
        nt <- 480
        ind <- 1:480
        period <- "Night"
        time.break <- c(1, floor(0.5 * grid_length), grid_length)
        time.label <- c("00:00","04:00", "08:00")
        legend.pos <- "none"
    }else if(period == "day"){
        nt <- 960
        ind <- 481:1440
        period <- "Daytime"
        time.label <- c("08:00", "12:00", "16:00", "20:00", "24:00")
        time.break <- c(1, floor(0.25 * grid_length), floor(0.5 * grid_length), floor(0.75 * grid_length), grid_length)
        legend.pos <- "right"
    }
    pctl <- 0.9
    data_analysis$func_cov   <- I(fpca.face(unclass(data_analysis$act_log_mat[,ind]))$Yhat)
    name_y <- expression(log(1 + AC))
    title <- paste0(period)
    
    ## fit AFCM
    data_analysis$t_int <- I(matrix(seq(0, 1, length.out = nt), ncol=nt, nrow=nrow(data_analysis), byrow=TRUE))
    data_analysis$l_int <- I(matrix(1/nt, ncol=nt, nrow=nrow(data_analysis)))
    fit_afc_period <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Employed + 
                              Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                              CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer +
                              ti(t_int, func_cov, by=l_int, bs=c("cr","cr"), k=c(5,5), mc = c(FALSE, TRUE)), 
                          weights=event, data=data_analysis, family=cox.ph())
    
    ## extract estimates
    sample <- data_analysis[1, c("Alcohol", "Overall_health", "PIR", "Age", "Employed", "BMI_cat", 
                                 "SmokeCigs", "Race", "Education", "CHD", "Diabetes", "CHF", "Stroke",
                                 "MobilityProblem", "Cancer")]
    grid_coef <- cal_grid(grid_length = 100, range_x = quantile(data_analysis$func_cov, pctl), range_s = 1) 
    sample_rep <- do.call("rbind", replicate(nrow(grid_coef), sample, simplify = FALSE))
    grid_coef <- cbind(grid_coef, sample_rep)
    real_coef_afc_period <- predict(fit_afc_period, newdata = grid_coef, type = 'terms')
    real_coef_afc_period <- matrix(real_coef_afc_period[,"ti(t_int,func_cov):l_int"], ncol = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), nrow = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), byrow = FALSE) # re-organize to matrix form
    
    ## plot the estimates
    grid_length <- nrow(real_coef_afc_period)
    range_x = quantile(data_analysis$func_cov, pctl)
    real_surf_afc_period <- ggplot(melt(real_coef_afc_period), aes(Var1,Var2, fill = value)) + 
        geom_raster() +
        scale_fill_gradientn(colours=c("blue3", "blue3", "#FFFFFF", "#FF0000"), name = expression(hat(F)(.,.))) +
        ggtitle(title) +
        scale_x_continuous(name = "Time of day",
                           breaks = time.break,
                           labels = time.label) +
        scale_y_continuous(name = name_y,
                           breaks = floor(seq(0, range_x, length.out = 5) / range_x * grid_length),
                           labels = round(seq(0, round(range_x, 2), length.out = 5), 2)) +
        theme_minimal() + 
        theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 15, hjust = 0.5),
              legend.position = legend.pos) 
    return(real_surf_afc_period)
}

Calculate cross-validated c-index and Briers score

To evaluate the predictive performance, we calculate and compare the cross-validated c-index and Briers score between additive functional Cox model (AFCM) and linear functional Cox model (LFCM). For each functional model, we use three physical activity measures, including unsmoothed LAC (unsmoothed), smoothed LAC (smoothed), and quantile-transformed smoothed LAC (smoothed + quantile). In addition, a Cox proportional hazard model (Cox PHM) is fit as the baseline using the average smoothed LAC of each individual as a scalar predictor. In total there are \(2\times 3+1 = 7\) combinations. Number of folds is chosen to be 10 to balance the amount of test data and the total number of validations. The c-index and Briers score of each model are stored in iAUC_* and iBrier_* respectively, where "*" indicates the exact model.

# cross validated c-index and Brier's score for each model
## introduce variables in the cross validation
set.seed(135) 
n_folds <- 10 # number of folds
### variables that store the c-index and Brier's score in each calculation
iAUC_afc <- iAUC_afc_sm <- iAUC_afc_sm_q <- iAUC_lfc <- iAUC_lfc_sm <- iAUC_lfc_sm_q <- iAUC_cph <- rep(0, n_folds)
iBrier_afc <- iBrier_afc_sm <- iBrier_afc_sm_q <- iBrier_lfc <- iBrier_lfc_sm <- iBrier_lfc_sm_q <- iBrier_cph <- rep(0, n_folds)
### use "createFolds" function from "caret" package to divide real data into n_folds folds
fold <- createFolds(data_analysis$time_mort, k = n_folds, list = FALSE)

### function "cal_c()" calculates Concordance using concordant vs discordant pairs empricical estimator
## marker = \hat\eta_i
## Stime = survival times
## status = event status (0 = censored, 1 = event)
cal_c <- function(marker, Stime, status){
    utimes <- sort(unique(Stime[status==1]))
    num <- denom <- 0
    for(ut in seq_along(utimes)){
        ## current time
        ti    <- utimes[ut]
        ## subjects who experienced an event at current time
        inx_i <- which(Stime == ti & status==1)
        ## subjects with observed times beyond event current time
        inx_j <- which(Stime > ti)
        ## number of "cases" and "controls" at time current time
        n_case_t    <- length(inx_i)
        n_control_t <- length(inx_j)
        for(i in seq_along(inx_i)){
            num   <- num + sum( (marker[inx_j] > marker[inx_i[i]] ) ) + 0.5*sum(marker[inx_j] == marker[inx_i[i]])
        }
        denom <- denom + n_case_t*n_control_t
    }
    1-num/denom
}

### function "cal_stime()" returns the survival times estimates on the test data in cross-validated prediction
cal_stime <- function(fit, tmax = 10, nt_pred = 1000, tgrid_sim = seq(0, 10, len=1000)){
    ## calculate estimated baseline hazard
    t0 <- rev(fit$family$data$tr)
    H0_hat <- rev(fit$family$data$h) ## estimate for the baseline cumulative hazard function \int_0^t \lambda_0(s)ds
    H0_fit <- gam(H0_hat ~ s(t0, pc = 0)-1) ## smooth the cumulative hazard
    ## evaluate smoothed H0 on fine grid
    tgrid_sim <- seq(0, tmax, len=nt_pred) ## potential grid of time points to simulate from
    H0_prd <- pmax(0, predict(H0_fit, newdata = data.frame(t0 = tgrid_sim))) ## truncate cumulative hazard at 0
    ## estimate eta from estimated functional surface of real data
    eta_i <- matrix(predict(fit, test_data), ncol = 1)
    ## calcualte survival times
    S_i <- exp(-(exp(eta_i) %*% H0_prd))
    return(S_i)
}

### function "cal_Brier()" calculates Brier's score under right censored survival setting
cal_Brier <- function(S, Stime, status, tgrid = seq(0, 10, len=1000)){
    iBrier <- 0
    utimes <- sort(unique(Stime[status == 1]))
    if(max(utimes) == 10){
        utimes <- utimes[-length(utimes)]
    }
    Brier.t <- rep(NA, length(utimes))
    for(ut in seq_along(utimes)){
        ## current time
        ti <- utimes[ut]
        ## subjects with observed times beyond event current time
        inx_j <- which(Stime > ti)
        ## subjects who experienced an event before or at current time
        inx_i <- which(Stime <= ti & status==1)
        ## extract survival probability of all subjects at this time
        surv.prob <- S[,max(which(tgrid <= ti))]
        tmp <- 0
        for(i in 1:nrow(S)){
            G <- 1
            if(i %in% inx_j){
                if(max(which(ut_test_censor < ti)) > 0){
                    G <- KM_test_censor[max(which(ut_test_censor < ti))]
                }
                tmp <- tmp + (1-surv.prob[i])^2/G
            }else if(i %in% inx_i){
                if(max(which(ut_test_censor < Stime[i])) > 0){
                    G <- KM_test_censor[max(which(ut_test_censor < Stime[i]))]
                }
                tmp <- tmp + (0-surv.prob[i])^2/G
            }
        }
        Brier.t[ut] <- tmp/nrow(S)
        if(ut == 1){
            iBrier <- iBrier + 0.5*utimes[ut]*Brier.t[ut]
        }else{
            iBrier <- iBrier + Brier.t[ut]*(utimes[ut] - utimes[ut-1])
        }
    }
    iBrier <- iBrier/max(utimes)
    return(iBrier)
}

## run cross validation
for(k in 1:n_folds){
    ## split train and test data
    train_data <- data_analysis[-which(fold == k),]
    test_data <- data_analysis[which(fold == k),]
    
    ## survival time and status
    time_test   <- test_data$time_mort
    event_test <- test_data$event
    time_train   <- train_data$time_mort
    event_train <- train_data$event
    
    ## get unique ordered survival times
    ut_train <- unique(time_train[event_train == 1])
    ut_train <- ut_train[order(ut_train)]
    ut_test <- unique(time_test[event_test == 1])
    ut_test <- ut_test[order(ut_test)]
    
    ## get KM estimates of survival function for train data
    KM_train <- unique(survfit(Surv(time_train,event_train)~1)$surv)
    ## get KM estimates of survival function for test data where test and training overlap
    ## impute linearly on the log scale for survival times which are not in the training dataset
    KM_test  <- rep(NA, length(ut_test))
    for(i in seq_along(ut_test)){
        ## if test data survival time less than the minimum observed event time in the training dataset
        ## impute survival time on the linearly log scale
        if(ut_test[i] < min(ut_train)){
            KM_test[i] <- exp(log(1) - (log(1) - log(KM_train[1])) / (ut_train[1]-0) * (ut_test[1]-0))
        }
        ## if test data survival time within the observed range of event times in the training dataset,
        ## either use the KM estimate (if the training time is in the test times), or impute linearly on the log scale
        if(ut_test[i] >= min(ut_train) & ut_test[i] < max(ut_train)){
            inx_l <- max(which(ut_train <= ut_test[i]))
            inx_r <- min(which(ut_train > ut_test[i]))
            st_l <- KM_train[inx_l]
            st_r <- KM_train[inx_r]
            t_l <- ut_train[inx_l]
            t_r <- ut_train[inx_r]
            KM_test[i] <- exp(log(st_l) - (log(st_l) - log(st_r))/(t_r -t_l)  * (ut_test[i] - t_l))
        }
        ## if the test data survival time is beyond the observe range of event times in the training dataset,
        ## use the last observed survival probability
        if(ut_test[i] >= max(ut_train)){
            KM_test[i] <- min(KM_train)
        }
    }
    
    ## derive the KM estimate of the censoring time
    ut_train_censor <- unique(time_train[event_train == 0])
    ut_train_censor <- ut_train_censor[order(ut_train_censor)]
    ut_test_censor <- unique(time_test[event_test == 0])
    ut_test_censor <- ut_test_censor[order(ut_test_censor)]
    ## get KM estimates of censoring time for train data
    KM_train_censor <- unique(survfit(Surv(time_train,1-event_train)~1)$surv)
    ## get KM estimates of censoring time for test data where test and training overlap
    ## impute linearly on the log scale for survival times which are not in the training dataset
    KM_test_censor  <- rep(NA, length(ut_test_censor))
    for(i in seq_along(ut_test_censor)){
        ## if test data survival time less than the minimum observed event time in the training dataset
        ## impute survival time on the linearly log scale
        if(ut_test_censor[i] < min(ut_train_censor)){
            KM_test_censor[i] <- exp(log(1) - (log(1) - log(KM_train_censor[1])) / (ut_train_censor[1]-0) * (ut_test_censor[1]-0))
        }
        ## if test data survival time within the observed range of event times in the training dataset,
        ## either use the KM estimate (if the training time is in the test times), or impute linearly on the log scale
        if(ut_test_censor[i] >= min(ut_train_censor) & ut_test_censor[i] < max(ut_train_censor)){
            inx_l <- max(which(ut_train_censor <= ut_test_censor[i]))
            inx_r <- min(which(ut_train_censor > ut_test_censor[i]))
            st_l <- KM_train_censor[inx_l]
            st_r <- KM_train_censor[inx_r]
            t_l <- ut_train_censor[inx_l]
            t_r <- ut_train_censor[inx_r]
            KM_test_censor[i] <- exp(log(st_l) - (log(st_l) - log(st_r))/(t_r -t_l)  * (ut_test_censor[i] - t_l))
        }
        ## if the test data survival time is beyond the observe range of event times in the training dataset,
        ## use the last observed survival probability
        if(ut_test_censor[i] >= max(ut_train_censor)){
            KM_test_censor[i] <- min(KM_train_censor)
        }
    }
    
    ## fit each model using train data
    ### AFCM
    fit_afc_cv <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Age + Employed + 
                          Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                          CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer +
                          ti(tmat, act_log_mat, by=lmat, bs=c("cc","cr"), k=c(5,5), mc = c(FALSE, TRUE)), weights=event, data=train_data, family=cox.ph())
    
    fit_afc_sm_cv <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Age + Employed + 
                             Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                             CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer +
                             ti(tmat, act_log_mat_sm, by=lmat, bs=c("cc","cr"), k=c(5,5), mc = c(FALSE, TRUE)), weights=event, data=train_data, family=cox.ph())

    fit_afc_sm_q_cv <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Age + Employed + 
                               Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                               CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer +
                               ti(tmat, act_log_mat_sm_q, by=lmat, bs=c("cc","cr"), k=c(5,5), mc = c(FALSE, TRUE)), weights=event, data=train_data, family=cox.ph())
    
    ### LFCM
    fit_lfc_cv <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Age + Employed + 
                          Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                          CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer + 
                          s(tmat, by = lmat * act_log_mat, bs="cc", k = 10), weights=event, data=train_data, family=cox.ph())
    
    fit_lfc_sm_cv <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Age + Employed + 
                             Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                             CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer + 
                             s(tmat, by = lmat * act_log_mat_sm, bs="cc", k = 10), weights=event, data=train_data, family=cox.ph())

    fit_lfc_sm_q_cv <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Age + Employed + 
                               Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                               CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer + 
                               s(tmat, by = lmat * act_log_mat_sm_q, bs="cc", k = 10), weights=event, data=train_data, family=cox.ph())
    
    ### Cox proportional hazard model
    fit_cph_cv <- gam(time_mort ~ Alcohol + Overall_health + PIR + Age + Employed + 
                          Age + BMI_cat + SmokeCigs + Race + Education +
                          CHD + Diabetes + CHF + Stroke + MobilityProblem + Cancer +
                          act_log_mat_ave, weights=event, data=train_data, family=cox.ph())
    
    ## obtain estimated log hazard (excluding baseline hazard)
    ### afc
    eta_afc_cv <- rowSums(predict(fit_afc_cv, test_data, type = "terms"))
    eta_afc_sm_cv <- rowSums(predict(fit_afc_sm_cv, test_data, type = "terms"))
    eta_afc_sm_q_cv <- rowSums(predict(fit_afc_sm_q_cv, test_data, type = "terms"))
    ### lfc
    eta_lfc_cv <- rowSums(predict(fit_lfc_cv, test_data, type="terms"))
    eta_lfc_sm_cv <- rowSums(predict(fit_lfc_sm_cv, test_data, type="terms"))
    eta_lfc_sm_q_cv <- rowSums(predict(fit_lfc_sm_q_cv, test_data, type="terms"))
    ### cph
    eta_cph_cv <- rowSums(predict(fit_cph_cv, test_data, type="terms"))
    
    ## derive cross-validated c-index
    iAUC_afc[k] <- cal_c(marker = eta_afc_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test)
    iAUC_afc_sm[k] <- cal_c(marker = eta_afc_sm_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test)
    iAUC_afc_sm_q[k] <- cal_c(marker = eta_afc_sm_q_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test)
    iAUC_lfc[k] <- cal_c(marker = eta_lfc_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test)
    iAUC_lfc_sm[k] <- cal_c(marker = eta_lfc_sm_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test)
    iAUC_lfc_sm_q[k] <- cal_c(marker = eta_lfc_sm_q_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test)
    iAUC_cph[k] <- cal_c(marker = eta_cph_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test)
    
    ## calculate the cross-validated brier score
    S_afc_cv <- cal_stime(fit = fit_afc_cv)
    S_afc_sm_cv <- cal_stime(fit = fit_afc_sm_cv)
    S_afc_sm_q_cv <- cal_stime(fit = fit_afc_sm_q_cv)
    S_lfc_cv <- cal_stime(fit = fit_lfc_cv)
    S_lfc_sm_cv <- cal_stime(fit = fit_lfc_sm_cv)
    S_lfc_sm_q_cv <- cal_stime(fit = fit_lfc_sm_q_cv)
    S_cph_cv <- cal_stime(fit = fit_cph_cv)
    
    tgrid_sim <- seq(0, 10, len=1000)
    iBrier_afc[k] <- cal_Brier(S_afc_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test, tgrid = tgrid_sim)
    iBrier_afc_sm[k] <- cal_Brier(S_afc_sm_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test, tgrid = tgrid_sim)
    iBrier_afc_sm_q[k] <- cal_Brier(S_afc_sm_q_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test, tgrid = tgrid_sim)
    iBrier_lfc[k] <- cal_Brier(S_lfc_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test, tgrid = tgrid_sim)
    iBrier_lfc_sm[k] <- cal_Brier(S_lfc_sm_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test, tgrid = tgrid_sim)
    iBrier_lfc_sm_q[k] <- cal_Brier(S_lfc_sm_q_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test, tgrid = tgrid_sim)
    iBrier_cph[k] <- cal_Brier(S_cph_cv, Stime = time_test, status = event_test, tgrid = tgrid_sim)
}

The result reported in Table 1 of the paper is shown below. Additive functional Cox model (AFCM) outperforms linear functional Cox model (LFCM) and baseline model (Cox PHM) with respect to the predictive performance. Simulation

Simulation framework

The simulation framework shown here consists of two parts: the simulation of functional covariates, and the simulation of survival data. The simulation of functional covariates is based on functional principal component analysis (FPCA). Denote \(\mu(s) = E(X(s))\), the simulated functional covariate \(\tilde{X}_i(s)\) is derived as \[\tilde{X}_i(s) = \hat{\mu}(s) + \sum_{j = 1}^M \sqrt{\hat{\lambda}_j} e_{ij} \hat{\psi}_j(s),\] where \(e_{ij}\) are i.i.d. \(N(0,1)\) random variables. The mean, \(\hat{\mu}(s)\), eigenvalues, \(\hat{\lambda}_j\), and eigenfunctions, \(\hat{\psi}_j(s)\), are estimated using fpca.face() function in the refund package. The sim_func_cov() function below implements this idea, and returns simulated functional covariates as a matrix.

## simulate functional covariate from real data
### function "sim_func_cov" simulate functional covariates using FPCA
#### real_func_cov: the matrix to simulate functional covariates from 
#### N: number of subjects to simulate
sim_func_cov <- function(real_func_cov, N){
    ## FPCA
    fit_fpca <- fpca.face(unclass(real_func_cov))
    
    ## extract estimated eigenfunctions/eigenvalues
    phi <- fit_fpca$efunctions
    lambda <- fit_fpca$evalues
    K <- length(fit_fpca$evalues)
    
    ## simulate random coefficients 
    theta <- matrix(rnorm(N*K), nrow=N, ncol=K)  # generate independent standard normals 
    theta <- theta %*% diag(sqrt(lambda))        # scale to have appropriate variance
    X_new <- theta %*% t(phi)                    # simulate new functions
    X_new <- X_new + t(fit_fpca$mu %o% rep(1,N))      # add back in the mean function
    return(X_new)
}

The procedure to simulate survival data is organized as follows: (1) derive the estimated cumulative baseline hazard function \(\tilde{\Lambda}_0(t)\); (2) derive the estimated linear predictor \(\tilde{\eta}_i\); (3) derive the estimated survival function \(\tilde{S}_i(t)\); (4) simulate survival time \(\tilde{T}_i\) from \(\tilde{S}_i(t)\); and (5) simulate censoring time \(\tilde{C}_i\) from the empirical distribution of censoring times in the NHANES data to control censoring rate.

The key component here is to derive the estimated linear predictor \(\tilde{\eta}_i\) in step (2). Two simulation components are considered. In the first component, the function \(F(\cdot, \cdot)\) is estimated from real data, implemented through sim_surv() function below. The simulated survival data, combined with the transformed simulated functional covariates, are returned as a data frame.

## simulate survival data from real data (NHANES here, but can be any types of functional data)
### function "sim_surv()" simulate survival data using estimated functional surface from real data
#### fit: the fitted model used to estimate cumulative hazard
#### N: number of subjects to simulate
#### X: functional covariates used to predict eta
#### tmax: upper bound of time points to simulate from
#### time_mort: time to event information from real data
#### event: event status information from real data
#### nt_pred: number of potential survival times
sim_surv <- function(fit, N, X, tmax, time_mort, event, nt_pred = 1000){
    ## calculate estimated baseline hazard
    t0 <- rev(fit$family$data$tr)
    H0_hat <- rev(fit$family$data$h) ## estimate for the baseline cumulative hazard function \int_0^t \lambda_0(s)ds
    H0_fit <- scam(H0_hat ~ s(t0, bs = "mpi")-1) ## smooth the cumulative hazard
    ## evaluate smoothed H0 on fine grid
    tgrid_sim <- seq(0, tmax, len=nt_pred) ## potential grid of time points to simulate from
    H0_prd <- pmax(0, predict(H0_fit, newdata = data.frame(t0 = tgrid_sim))) ## truncate cumulative hazard at 0
    H0_prd[1] <- 0
    
    ## combine functional covariates with necessary elements in model fitting
    nt <- ncol(X)
    tind <- seq(0, 1, length.out = nt)
    data_sim <- data.frame(func_cov = I(X), 
                           l_int = I(matrix(1/nt, ncol = nt, nrow = N)),
                           t_int = I(matrix(tind, ncol = nt, nrow = N, byrow = TRUE)))
    
    ## estimate eta from estimated functional surface of real data
    eta_i <- predict(fit, newdata = data_sim, type = 'terms')
    
    ## calcualte survival times
    S_i <- exp(-(exp(eta_i) %*% H0_prd))
    U   <- runif(N)
    Ti  <- rep(NA, N)
    for(i in 1:N){
        if(all(S_i[i,] > U[i])){
            Ti[i] <- max(tgrid_sim) + 1
        } else {
            Ti[i] <- tgrid_sim[min(which(S_i[i,] < U[i]))]
        }
    }
    
    ## simulate censoring times from empirical distribution
    C_i <- sample(time_mort[event == 0], size=N, replace=TRUE)
    
    ## create simulated censoring indicator based on "true" event time S_i and censoring time C_i
    Ti_obs <- pmin(C_i, Ti)
    di <- as.numeric(Ti <= C_i)
    
    ## combine the simulated survival data in a data frame
    data_sim <- data.frame(data_sim, time_mort = Ti_obs, event=di)
    data_sim$act_log_mat_ave <- rowSums(data_sim$func_cov) / ncol(data_sim$func_cov)
    
    return(data_sim)
}

In the second component, the functional surface \(F(\cdot, \cdot)\) is pre-specified, implemented through sim_surv_F() function. We consider four different forms of \(F(\cdot, \cdot)\): (1) \(F(s, x) = 2x\) (model_type = "const"); (2) \(F(s, x) = xs\) (model_type = "linear"); (3) \(F(s, x) = x^3 s\) (model_type = "nonlinear1"); and (4) \(F(s, x) = \sin{xs}\) (model_type = "nonlinear2"). This function also returns a data frame containing both the transformed simulated functional covariates and simulated survival data.

## simulate survival data with pre-specified F(.,.)
### function "sim_surv_F()" simulate survival data using pre-specified F(.,.)
#### fit: the model used to estimate cumulative hazard
#### N: number of subjects to simulate
#### tmax: upper bound of time points to simulate from
#### time_mort: time to event from real data
#### event: event status from real data
#### nt_pred: number of potential survival times
#### model: name of the specified F(.,.)
#### range_x: upper bound of functional value domain, 1 by default
#### range_s: upper bound of functional domain, 1 by default
sim_surv_F <- function(fit, N, tmax, time_mort, event, nt_pred = 1000, model = "linear", range_x = 1, range_s = 1){
    ## calculate estimated baseline hazard
    t0 <- rev(fit$family$data$tr)
    H0_hat <- rev(fit$family$data$h) ## estimate for the baseline cumulative hazard function \int_0^t \lambda_0(s)ds
    H0_fit <- scam(H0_hat ~ s(t0, bs = "mpi")-1)
    ## evaluate smoothed H0 on fine grid
    tgrid_sim <- seq(0, tmax, len=nt_pred) ## potential grid of time points to simulate from
    H0_prd <- pmax(0, predict(H0_fit, newdata = data.frame(t0 = tgrid_sim))) ## truncate cumulative hazard at 0
    H0_prd[1] <- 0
    
    ## define pre-specified functional coefficient surface F(.,.), labeled as beta
    if(model == "linear"){
        beta <- function(X, s) X*s
    }else if(model == "const"){
        beta <- function(X, s) X*2
    }else if(model == "nonlinear1"){
        beta <- function(X, s) (X^3)*s
    }else if(model == "nonlinear2"){
        beta <- function(X, s) sin(X*s)
    }
    
    ## simulate functional covariate from FPCA
    X_new <- sim_func_cov(data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm, N)
    X_new <- I(apply(X_new, 2,function(y) ecdf(y)(y))) * range_x * 2
    X_new <- sweep(X_new, 2, colMeans(X_new)) ## mean center simulated functional covariates
    
    ## combine functional covariates with necessary elements in model fitting
    nt <- ncol(X_new)
    tind <- seq(0, range_s, length.out = nt)
    data_sim <- data.frame(func_cov = I(X_new), 
                           l_int = I(matrix(1/nt, ncol = nt, nrow = N)),
                           t_int = I(matrix(tind, ncol = nt, nrow = N, byrow = TRUE)))
    
    # calculate eta_i using numerical intergration given pre-specified F
    eta_i <- as.matrix(apply(X_new, 1, function(x) sum(beta(X=x, s=tind))/nt), ncol = 1)
    
    ## calcualte survival times
    S_i <- exp(-(exp(eta_i) %*% H0_prd))
    U   <- runif(N)
    Ti  <- rep(NA, N)
    for(i in 1:N){
        if(all(S_i[i,] > U[i])){
            Ti[i] <- max(tgrid_sim) + 1
        } else {
            Ti[i] <- tgrid_sim[min(which(S_i[i,] < U[i]))]
        }
    }
    
    ## simulate censoring times from empirical distribution
    C_i <- sample(time_mort[event == 0], size=N, replace=TRUE)
    
    ## Create simulated censoring indicator based on "true" event time S_i and censoring time C_i
    Ti_obs <- pmin(C_i, Ti)
    di <- as.numeric(Ti <= C_i)
    
    ## combine the simulated survival data in a data frame
    data_sim <- data.frame(data_sim, time_mort = Ti_obs, event=di)
    data_sim$act_log_mat_ave <- rowSums(data_sim$func_cov) / ncol(data_sim$func_cov)
    
    return(data_sim)
}

Some functions introduced in the application section are slightly modified for simulation use.

### a similar function to "cal_grid", add variables to flexibly control the boundary of the grid
cal_grid_sim <- function(grid_length = 100, x_lo = -1, x_up = 1, s_lo = 0, s_up = 2){
    tind_pred <- seq(s_lo, s_up, length.out = grid_length)
    xind_pred <- seq(x_lo, x_up, length.out = grid_length)
    grid_coef <- data.frame(t_int = rep(tind_pred, grid_length),
                            func_cov = rep(xind_pred, each = grid_length),
                            l_int=1)
    return(grid_coef)
}

### a similar function to "vis_surf", modify variables to improve plotting efficiency in the simulation
vis_surf_sim <- function(coef, x_lo = -1, x_up = 1, s_lo = 0, s_up = 2, name, lb = 0, ub = 1, fontsize = 12){
  coef_plot <- melt(coef) # re-organize to plot form
  grid_length <- nrow(coef)

  bound <- c(lb, ub)
  color <- c("blue3", "#FFFFFF", "red2")
  surf <- ggplot(coef_plot, aes(Var1,Var2, fill = value)) + 
    geom_raster() +
    scale_fill_gradientn(colours=color, name = expression(hat(F)(.,.)), limits = bound) +
    ggtitle(name) +
    scale_x_continuous(name = "Functional domain",
                       breaks = floor(seq(0, grid_length, length.out = 6)), 
                       labels = seq(s_lo, s_up, length.out = 6)) +
    scale_y_continuous(name = "Value of functional covariate",
                       breaks = floor(seq(0, grid_length, length.out = 6)), 
                       labels = seq(x_lo, x_up, length.out = 6)) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = fontsize, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))

  return(surf)
}

Simulation when \(F(\cdot, \cdot)\) is estimated from real data

Our simulation framework requires to first build a baseline additive functional Cox model \[\log \lambda_i(t|\mathbf{X}_i) = \log \lambda_0(t) + \int_\mathcal{S} F[s, h_{is}(X_i(s))]ds\;,\] which only includes a functional covariate and no other covariate. The model is fit and stored in fit_afc_real, is only for simulation purpose and does not have practical intepretations. We use the quantile-transformed smoothed LAC to fit the model considering its fine coverage on the grid. In other words, the correctly specified \(h_{is}\) is the quantile transformation.

## fit the baseline AFCM using quantile-transformed functional predictors
## this model is only for simulation purpose, different from application!
data_analysis$func_cov <- data_analysis$act_log_mat_sm_q
data_analysis$t_int <- data_analysis$tmat 
data_analysis$l_int <- data_analysis$lmat
fit_afc_real <- gam(time_mort ~ ti(t_int, func_cov, by=l_int, bs=c("cc","cr"), k=c(10,10), mc=c(FALSE, TRUE)),
                    weights=event, data=data_analysis, family=cox.ph())

The baseline surface, that is, the estimated surface from baseline AFCM, is then derived following a similar procedure as in the application. We also extract estimated cumulative baseline hazards from baseline AFCM on a prespecified grid.

To quantify the simulation performance, we calculate the integrated square error (ISE) for each number of simulated subjects. The ISE is defined as \[\text{ISE}(\hat{F}(s, x)) = \int_\mathcal{S} \int_\mathcal{X} (\hat{F}(s, x) - F(s, x))^2 dxds\;.\] Here we give an example on drawing the boxplot of ISE based on the 10 simulations. The ISE calculation for estimated cumulative baseline hazards is performed analogously.

## calculate integrated square error (ISE)
### function "cal_ISE()" calculate the ISE of simulations and return a format ready for visualization
#### nsim: number of simulations
#### sim_coef: the estimated functional surface from simulated data of nsim simulations
#### real_coef: the estimated functional surface from real data
cal_ISE <- function(nsim, sim_coef, real_coef, N_pred){
    ISE <- rep(0, nsim)
    for(i in 1:nsim){
        ISE[i] <- sum((sim_coef[i,,] - real_coef)^2) / (ncol(real_coef) * nrow(real_coef))
    }
    ISE.df <- data.frame(N = rep(as.character(N_pred), nsim), ISE = ISE)
    
    return(ISE.df)
}
ISE.df <- cal_ISE(nsim = nsim, sim_coef = sim_coef, real_coef = real_coef, N_pred = 2000)

ggplot(ISE.df, aes(x = N, y = ISE)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = N)) +
  xlab("Sample size") +
  ylab("ISE") +
  ggtitle("Integrated squared error") +
  theme_light() +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 8),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 8),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))

Simulation with pre-specified forms of \(F(\cdot, \cdot)\)

In the second simulation component, four different forms of \(F(\cdot, \cdot)\) are used to simulate survival data with formulas given above. We provide a sample code to run nsim = 5 simulations with N_pred = 5000 subjects per simulation when model_type = "nonlinear1", that is, when true function \(F(s, x) = x^3s\). Other cases can be implemented analogously. The estimated surface based on our model (AFCM) and linear functional Cox model (LFCM) are stored in sim_coef_afc and sim_coef_lfc respectively.

## introduce variables in the simulation
model_type = "nonlinear1" ## type of F(.,.) to pre-specify, have "const", "linear", "nonlinear1" and "nonlinear2" options corresponding the manuscript
range_x <- 2 ## range of functional value domain
range_s <- 2 ## range of functional domain
nsim <- 5 ## number of iterations
N_pred <- 5000 ## number of subjects to simulate per simulation
sim_coef_afc <- array(NA, dim=c(nsim, 100, 100)) ## store coef matrix for each simulation
sim_coef_lfc <- array(NA, dim=c(nsim, 100, 100)) ## store coef matrix for each simulation
sim_CBH_afc <- matrix(NA, nrow = nsim, ncol = nt_pred) ## store CBH for each simulation
sim_CBH_lfc <- matrix(NA, nrow = nsim, ncol = nt_pred) ## store CBH for each simulation

set.seed(534)
## simulation
for(m in 1:nsim){
    ## simulate functional covariate and survival data 
    data_sim <- sim_surv_F(fit = fit_afc_real, N = N_pred, tmax = 10, range_x = range_x, range_s = range_s,
                           time_mort = data_analysis$time_mort, event = data_analysis$event, model = model_type)
    
    ## fit the AFCM and LFCM model using simulated data, derive estimated surface and cumulative baseline hazards
    grid_coef <- cal_grid_sim(grid_length = 100, x_lo = -1, x_up = 1, s_lo = 0, s_up = 2)
    
    ### 1. AFCM
    fit_afc_sim <- gam(time_mort ~ ti(t_int, func_cov, by=l_int, bs=c("cr","cr"), k=c(5, 5), mc=c(FALSE,TRUE)), weights = event, data = data_sim, family = cox.ph())
    sim_afc_res <- predict(fit_afc_sim, newdata = grid_coef, type = 'terms')
    sim_coef_afc[m,,] <- matrix(sim_afc_res[,"ti(t_int,func_cov):l_int"], ncol = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), nrow = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), byrow = FALSE) # re-organize to matrix form
    
    t0 <- rev(fit_afc_sim$family$data$tr)
    H0_hat <- rev(fit_afc_sim$family$data$h) ## estimate for the baseline cumulative hazard function
    H0_fit <- scam(H0_hat ~ s(t0, bs = "mpi")-1) ## smooth the cumulative hazard
    sim_CBH_afc[m,] <- pmax(0, predict(H0_fit, newdata = data.frame(t0 = tgrid_sim))) ## truncate cumulative hazard at 0
    sim_CBH_afc[m,1] <- 0
    
    ### 2. LFCM
    fit_lfc_sim <- gam(time_mort ~ s(t_int, by = l_int * func_cov, bs="cr", k = 10), weights=event, data=data_sim, family=cox.ph())
    sim_lfc_res <- predict(fit_lfc_sim, newdata = grid_coef, type = 'terms')
    sim_coef_lfc[m,,] <- matrix(sim_lfc_res[,"s(t_int):l_int * func_cov"], ncol = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), nrow = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), byrow = FALSE)
    
    t0 <- rev(fit_lfc_sim$family$data$tr)
    H0_hat <- rev(fit_lfc_sim$family$data$h) ## estimate for the baseline cumulative hazard function
    H0_fit <- scam(H0_hat ~ s(t0, bs = "mpi")-1) ## smooth the cumulative hazard
    sim_CBH_afc[m,] <- pmax(0, predict(H0_fit, newdata = data.frame(t0 = tgrid_sim))) ## truncate cumulative hazard at 0
    sim_CBH_afc[m,1] <- 0
}

Similar with the first scenario, we calculate the the integrated squared error (ISE) between each estimated surface and real surface. The boxplot is shown below. Even with 10 simulations, AFCM substantially outperforms LFCM when \(F(\cdot, \cdot)\) is nonlinear with respect to \(x\).

### a similar function with "cal_ISE", introduce "F_form" for flexible notation
cal_ISE_F <- function(nsim, sim_coef, real_coef, F_form, model_name){
    ISE <- rep(0, nsim)
    for(i in 1:nsim){
        ISE[i] <- sum((sim_coef[i,,] - real_coef)^2) / (ncol(real_coef) * nrow(real_coef))
    }
    ISE.df <- data.frame(F_form = rep(as.character(F_form), nsim), ISE = ISE, model = rep(as.character(model_name), nsim))
    
    return(ISE.df)
}

Comparing the performance of two approaches to ensure identifiability

As discussed in the supplementary materials, we can use two approaches to ensure identifiability. The first approach first derives an unconstrained estimate, then subtracts its corresponding sample means. The second approach, instead, directly imposes the identifiability constraints using ti() function when fitting the model. We here provide the code to implement both approaches. The plot shows true surface (\(F(s, x) = xs\)), average unconstrained estimates, and average constrained estimates using both approaches, labeled as te + post-hoc and ti, from 5 simulations. Both approaches work well in this simulation setting. The unconstrained estimates indicate the importance of additional constraints discussed in Section 2.3 of the paper.

model_type = "linear"
range_x <- 2 ## range of functional value domain
range_s <- 2 ## range of functional domain
nsim <- 5 ## number of iterations
N_pred <- 5000 ## number of subjects to simulate per simulation
sim_coef_afc_raw <- array(NA, dim=c(nsim, 100, 100)) ## array to store coef matrix for each simulation
sim_coef_afc_teph <- array(NA, dim=c(nsim, 100, 100)) 
sim_coef_afc_ti <- array(NA, dim=c(nsim, 100, 100))

set.seed(129)
ptm <- proc.time()
## simulation
for(m in 1:nsim){
    ## simulate functional covariate and survival data 
    data_sim <- sim_surv_F(fit = fit_afc_real, N = N_pred, tmax = 10, range_x = range_x, range_s = range_s,
                           time_mort = data_analysis$time_mort, event = data_analysis$event, model = model_type)
    ## build the grid to estimate
    grid_coef <- cal_grid_sim(grid_length = 100, x_lo = -1, x_up = 1, s_lo = 0, s_up = 2)
    
    ## 1.fit an unconstrained model
    fit_afc_sim <- gam(time_mort ~ te(t_int, func_cov, by = l_int, bs = c("cr","cr"),k=c(5, 5)), weights = event, data = data_sim, family = cox.ph())
    coef_afc <- predict(fit_afc_sim, newdata = grid_coef, type = 'terms')
    ### unconstrained estimate
    sim_coef_afc_raw[m,,] <- matrix(coef_afc[,"te(t_int,func_cov):l_int"], ncol = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), nrow = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), byrow = FALSE) # re-organize to matrix form
    ### ensure identifiability by post-hoc correction
    sim_coef_afc_teph[m,,] <- sim_coef_afc_raw[m,,] - rowMeans(sim_coef_afc_raw[m,,]) ## impose post-hoc identifiability constraint
    
    ## 2.fit a constrained model
    fit_afc_cst <- gam(time_mort ~ ti(t_int, func_cov, by=l_int, bs=c("cr","cr"), k=c(5, 5), mc=c(FALSE, TRUE)), weights = event, data = data_sim, family = cox.ph())
    coef_afc_cst <- predict(fit_afc_cst, newdata = grid_coef, type = 'terms')
    sim_coef_afc_ti[m,,] <- matrix(coef_afc_cst[,"ti(t_int,func_cov):l_int"], ncol = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), nrow = sqrt(nrow(grid_coef)), byrow = FALSE) # re-organize to matrix form
}
proc.time() - ptm
##    user  system elapsed 
## 530.729 178.334 882.224
## derive and plot the estimates
sim_surf_afc_raw <- vis_surf_sim(coef = apply(sim_coef_afc_raw, c(2, 3), mean), x_lo = -1, x_up = 1, s_lo = 0, s_up = 2, name = "AFCM, mgcv default", lb = -2.2, ub = 2.2, fontsize = 10) 
sim_surf_afc_teph <- vis_surf_sim(coef = apply(sim_coef_afc_teph, c(2, 3), mean), x_lo = -1, x_up = 1, s_lo = 0, s_up = 2, name = "AFCM, te + post-hoc", lb = -2.2, ub = 2.2, fontsize = 10) 
sim_surf_afc_ti <- vis_surf_sim(coef = apply(sim_coef_afc_ti, c(2, 3), mean), x_lo = -1, x_up = 1, s_lo = 0, s_up = 2, name = "AFCM, ti", lb = -2.2, ub = 2.2, fontsize = 10) 

## true surface
xind <- as.matrix(seq(-1, 1, len = 100), ncol = 1)
tind <- as.matrix(seq(0, 2, len = 100), ncol = 1)
real_coef_linear <- t((xind %*% t(tind)))
real_surf_linear <- vis_surf_sim(coef = real_coef_linear, x_lo = -1, x_up = 1, s_lo = 0, s_up = 2, name = "F(s,x) = xs", lb = -2.2, ub = 2.2, fontsize = 10)

grid.arrange(real_surf_linear, sim_surf_afc_raw, sim_surf_afc_teph, sim_surf_afc_ti, nrow = 2)
